        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The array configuration and mosaic mapping
The most important interest of this project is to know the minimum size and the size distribution of the small scale cloud structures.  We thus need to have high sensitivities to wide range of angular frequencies of the structures.  By combined with the 45m OTF map, we aim to sample the size range from a few 100 AU to 10000 AU, and thus require ~ 3˝ angular resolution. Because the minimum baseline of the 12m array is less than 45m, no ACA is needed to fulfill the zero spacing UV.  From the result of the ALMA simulator on CASA, the second compact configuration is suitable to sample small cloud structures (see Fig. 4).
Also we aim to take 95 mosaic field to cover fairly large area and sample as many cloudlets as possible to have better statistics using the 45m CO map as a guide. The mosaic field was carefully chosen where faint and unresolved CO clouds are likely to exist, and it is separated from the main cloud to avoid the contaminating signal coming through the antenna side lobes, although the side lobe level is small enough.

The correlator setup
The internal velocity dispersion of the thermalized unit cloudlets would be dV ~ 0.3 km/s.  We use slightly over-sampling correlator mode of 30.5 kHz resolution, corresponding to 0.08 km/s channel width.  For the sensitivity calculation, 0.3 km/s velocity resolution is used.  There is no other lines detectable in band 3, since the 12CO 1-0 line is already faint, the other 3 basebands are used to take continuum in the TDM mode to see the dust cloud distribution.  

Sensitivity and time estimation
As shown in Fig. 3, the small scale structures seem to be blended in the single-dish beam, and the ensemble spectra appears to be a broad line with the radiative temperature of ~ 1 K suffering from the beam dilution.  They are expected to have sizes of a few arcsec to 20˝ resolved by the synthesized beam, having higher Tr* (~ 3 K similar to that of Fig. 2) and smaller dV (close to the sound speed ~ 0.3 km/s).  With the 0.3 km/s velocity resolution and 3˝ spatial resolution, 0.7 K 1sigma mosaic sensitivity is required to detect such structures.  By making 95-pointing mosaic observation, OT estimate the total time for science goal as 50 min.  
Although our main goal is to detect cloudlets in CO lines, continuum data with 0.4 mJy 1sigma sensitivity per baseband would help us detecting the dust thermal emission from the small-scale structure even if molecule is photo dissociated. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
